Adjacency matrix of a signed graph.
For a signed graph G^{\sigma} of order n, the adjacency matrix A(G^{\sigma})=[a^{\sigma}\_{ij}] is defined by

|  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- |
|  | a^{\sigma}\_{ij}=\begin{cases}\sigma(v\_{i}v\_{j}),&\text{if }v\_{i}\sim v\_{j},\\[% 4.0pt] 0,&\text{otherwise}.\end{cases} |  |

Thus the sign pattern of G^{\sigma} is encoded directly in the entries of A(G^{\sigma}).
Since A(G^{\sigma}) is real and symmetric, all eigenvalues are real and may be ordered as

|  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- |
|  | \lambda\_{1}\geq\lambda\_{2}\geq\cdots\geq\lambda\_{n}. |  |

The adjacency spectrum of G^{\sigma}, denoted \mathrm{Spec}\_{A}(G,\sigma), is the multiset of eigenvalues of A(G^{\sigma}) counted with algebraic multiplicity.
For an eigenvalue \lambda, its multiplicity is denoted m(G^{\sigma},\lambda).
Because A(G^{\sigma}) is diagonalizable, the algebraic and geometric multiplicities coincide.
The rank of a signed graph is \operatorname{rank}(G^{\sigma})=\operatorname{rank}(A(G^{\sigma})), and for any eigenvalue \lambda\in\mathbb{R},

|  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- |
|  | m(G^{\sigma},\lambda)=n-\operatorname{rank}(\lambda I-A(G^{\sigma})). |  |

Balance via switching.
A classical result of Harary, restated by Zaslavsky in [16], characterizes balance in terms of switching:

###### Lemma 1.

Let G^{\sigma}=(G,\sigma) be a signed graph.
Then G^{\sigma} is balanced if and only if (G,\sigma)\sim(G,+), where (G,+) is the all-positive signing of G.